  With SASS you can create shared variables <code>config</code> & set 
  of mixins for CSS properties with vendor prefixes. Also it is extremely 
  useful to control specific IE versions support by creating mixins for 
  cross-browser compatible <code>inline-block</code> or 
  <code>opacity</code> Finally you save time writing less. Here is an 
  example of a typical config:

  %pre<
    %code<
      :preserve
        // Colors
        $base-color: #000
        $opaque:     #333
        $neutral:    #666
        $pale:       #999
        $bare:       #aaa
        $firm:       #9bc345
        $sharp:      #fff
        $contrast:   #000
        $positive:   #9cc346
        $negative:   #c34646
        $link:       #0072ff
        
        // Typography
        $base-font: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif
        $firm-font: Georgia, serif
        $h1: 24px
        $h2: 20px
        $h3: 18px
        $h4: 16px
        $h5: 15px
        $h6: 11px
        $base-font-size: 14px
        
        // Spaces
        $space-x: 3px
        $space-s: 5px
        $space-m: 10px
        $space-l: 20px  #p9

